What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 999 students' exam scores in three subjects (math, reading and writing). The dataset contains 999 observations and 9 variables. The variables include: 'gender', 'race/ethnicity', 'parental level of education', 'lunch', 'test preparation course', 'math score', 'reading score', 'writing score' and 'average_score'. There are four numrical variables (which include 'math score', 'reading score', 'writing score' and 'average_score') and five categorical variables (which include 'gender', 'race/ethnicity', 'parental level of education', 'lunch', and 'test preparation course') in the dataset.

The categorical variables in the dataset are nominal while the numerical variables are discrete.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting students' performance in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that test preparation course will have the strongest effect on each student's performance: I believe that those students who completed a test preparation course will perform better than those who did not. I also think that parental level of education will have some effects on each student's performance: the higher the parental level of education, the better the performance.

# defining functions for plotting visuals.
def univariate_visualization(variable_in_quotes):
    numerical_var = df.columns[5:]
    bar_chart_variables = ['parental level of education', 'race/ethnicity']
    
    if variable_in_quotes in numerical_var:
        plt.figure(figsize=[10, 6])
        bins = np.arange(10, df[variable_in_quotes].max()+5, 5)
        ticks = np.arange(10, df[variable_in_quotes].max()+10, 10)
        labels = [f'{int(i)}' for i in ticks]
        plt.hist(data=df, x=variable_in_quotes, bins=bins)
        plt.xticks(ticks, labels)
        plt.title(f'Distribution of {variable_in_quotes}'.upper(), fontsize=14, y=1.05)
        plt.xlabel(variable_in_quotes, fontsize=12)
        plt.ylabel('count', fontsize=12);
    else:
        if variable_in_quotes in bar_chart_variables:
            rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 8,5
            plt.title(f'Distribution of {variable_in_quotes}'.upper(), y=1.05, fontsize=14)
            count_order = df[variable_in_quotes].value_counts()
            sns.countplot(data = df, y = variable_in_quotes, color=sns.color_palette()[0], order = count_order.index);
            rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 8,5
            for i in range(count_order.shape[0]):
                count = count_order[i]
                bar_prop_label = f'{round((count/count_order.sum())*100,1)}%'
                plt.text(count+1, i, bar_prop_label, va='center')
        else:
            plt.figure(figsize=[7,7])
            rcParams['font.size']=16
            if variable_in_quotes == 'test preparation course':
                labels=['not completed', 'completed']
                colors=['#0b0918','#10485288']
            elif variable_in_quotes == 'gender':
                labels = ['Male', 'Female']
                colors=['#0d1335', '#bc5090']
            elif variable_in_quotes == 'lunch':
                labels = ['standard', 'free/reduced']
                colors=['#003f5c', '#bc5090']
            _, _, autotexts = plt.pie(df[variable_in_quotes].value_counts(), labels=labels, colors=colors,
                                      startangle=90, counterclock=False, shadow=True, explode=(0, 0.08), autopct='%1.1f%%')
            for figure in autotexts:
                figure.set_color('white')
            plt.title(variable_in_quotes.upper())
    plt.show;
         
def bivariate_visualization(numerical_var_in_quotes, categorical_var_in_quotes):
    if categorical_var_in_quotes == 'race/ethnicity' or categorical_var_in_quotes == 'parental level of education':
        size = (6,25)
        nrows = 3
        ncols = 1
        fontsize = 12
        rotation=10
        x = categorical_var_in_quotes
        y = numerical_var_in_quotes
        bar_palette=['#003f5c']
        if categorical_var_in_quotes == 'parental level of education':
            xlabel = ''
        else:
            xlabel = categorical_var_in_quotes
    else:
        size = (22,6)
        nrows = 1
        ncols = 3
        fontsize=18
        rotation=0
        x = categorical_var_in_quotes
        y = numerical_var_in_quotes
        bar_palette=['#003f5c', '#bc5090']
        xlabel = categorical_var_in_quotes
        
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':size})
    plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, 1)
    plt.title(f'Box Plot of {numerical_var_in_quotes} for {categorical_var_in_quotes}'.upper(), fontsize=12, y=1.05)
    sns.boxplot(data = df, y = y, x = x, color = sns.color_palette()[-1], palette=['#003f5c', '#bc5090'])
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=fontsize)
    plt.ylabel(numerical_var_in_quotes, fontsize= fontsize)
    plt.xticks(fontsize= fontsize, rotation=rotation)
       
    plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, 2)
    plt.title(f'Violin Plot of {numerical_var_in_quotes} for {categorical_var_in_quotes}'.upper(), fontsize=12, y=1.05)
    sns.violinplot(data = df, y = y, x = x, palette=['#003f5c', '#bc5090'], inner='quartile')
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=fontsize)
    plt.ylabel(numerical_var_in_quotes, fontsize=fontsize)
    plt.xticks(fontsize= fontsize, rotation=rotation)

    plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, 3)
    plt.title(f'Bar Chart of {numerical_var_in_quotes} for {categorical_var_in_quotes}'.upper(), fontsize=12, y=1.05)
    sns.barplot(data = df, x = categorical_var_in_quotes, y = numerical_var_in_quotes, palette = bar_palette)
    plt.xlabel(categorical_var_in_quotes, fontsize=fontsize)
    plt.ylabel(numerical_var_in_quotes, fontsize=fontsize)
    plt.xticks(fontsize= fontsize, rotation=90)
    plt.show;
   
def multivariate_violin(numerical_var_in_quotes, categorical_var_in_qoutes, categorical_hue_in_quotes):
    rcParams['figure.figsize']= 10,6
    sns.violinplot(data=df, x=categorical_var_in_qoutes, y=numerical_var_in_quotes, hue=categorical_hue_in_quotes, inner='quartile', palette=['#bc5090','#10485288'], split=True)
    plt.xlabel(categorical_var_in_qoutes)
    plt.ylabel(numerical_var_in_quotes)
    plt.title(f'Violin plot of {numerical_var_in_quotes} of {categorical_var_in_qoutes} based on their {categorical_hue_in_quotes} status'.upper())
    plt.show();

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The analysis shows that parental level of education has a great impact on students performance. It was observed that children of parents with high education such as master's degree, bachelor's degree and associate degree performed better than children of parents with low education.

Expectedly, there is a very high linear correlation between reading score and writing score, indicating that a student who did well in one also did well in the other. Same goes with the math score and the other numerical variables.

More importantly, the analysis revealed that our variable of interest, test preparation course, had the expected impact on student performance as students who completed a test preparation course performed extremely better than those who did not.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

It is observed that female students performed better than male students. However male students are better at math as shown in the analysis. Also, lunch had a very strong impact on students' performance: students who had standard lunch performed extremely better than those who had free/reduced lunch.

# Creating a new column for two categories of parents: high education and low education parents.
degree_parents = []
for i in df['parental level of education'].values:
    if 'degree' in i:
        degree_parents.append('high')
    else:
        degree_parents.append('low')
df["parents' educational status"] = degree_parents

# savng the new dataset
df.to_csv('new_exam_data.csv')

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

My multivariate exploration focussed on finding out the variable with the strongest impact on students' performance since the bivariate exploration revealed that parental level of education, test preparation course, lunch and gender are the determinants of students' performance.

The analysis revealed that students of parents with low education who completed a test preparation course performed better than students of parents with high education who did not undergo a test preparation course. Also, students of parents with low education who had standard lunch performed better than students of parents with high education who had free or reduced lunch. This indicates that both test preparation course and lunch have stronger impact on students' performance than parental level of eduction.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The result of the analysis showed that students who had standard lunch but did not undergo a test preparation course performed better than students who completed a test preparation course but had free or reduced lunch. This shows that lunch had a greater effect on students' performance than test preparation course.

Conclusion¶

From the foregoing, it is obvious that lunch has the strongest impact on students' performance. Against all odds, students who have standard lunch perform better than students who have all other advantages except a standard lunch. In addition to lunch, test preparation course also have a strong impact on students' performance. It was observed in this analysis that students who completed a test preparation course performed better than others even when others have the advantage of high level of parental education. The feature with the weakest impact on students' performance is parent level of education. Althogh children of parents with high education performed better than those with low parental education, this feature did not weigh heavily when compared to other features.
